{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17564717","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17564717"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:17:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:17:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17134"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17134","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17134"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.7,0.05,0.13,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9824"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103159"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9824","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9824"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17134"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85604"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1804"},{"type":"tags","id":"2343"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2877"},{"type":"tags","id":"2901"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23004"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43685"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45041"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103159","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103159"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old Aboriginal woman presents to the nephrology clinic for review. Five years ago she presented to hospital with a two-month history of joint pain and fatigue. She had oral ulcers, non-scarring alopecia and synovitis in the small joints in both hands. Investigations at that time revealed multiple abnormalities including positive antinuclear antibodies with a titre of 1:640 and autoimmune haemolytic anaemia. She was commenced on treatment and has since been in remission.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigation results would most strongly suggest a relapse of this condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Low C3 level, low C4 level, low anti-dsDNA level","Low C3 level, low C4 level, high anti-dsDNA level","High C3 level, high C4 level, low anti-dsDNA level","Low C3 level, high C4 level, high anti-dsDNA level","High C3 level, low C4 level, high anti-dsDNA level"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE) based on her initial presentation with characteristic features including oral ulcers, non-scarring alopecia, synovitis, positive ANA, and autoimmune haemolytic anaemia. Disease monitoring is essential even during periods of remission.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow C3 level, low C4 level, high anti-dsDNA level\u003C/strong\u003E is the combination that most strongly suggests active disease. Complement proteins are consumed during active inflammation in SLE, leading to low levels. Anti-dsDNA antibodies are highly specific for SLE, and rising levels correlate with disease activity. This pattern typically precedes clinical flares.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow C3 level, low C4 level, low anti-dsDNA level\u003C/strong\u003E is not the best answer, as whilst low complement levels are concerning, a low anti-dsDNA level is discordant with a lupus flare.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh C3 level, high C4 level, low anti-dsDNA level\u003C/strong\u003E is a pattern to unlikely suggest a lupus flare, as normal or high complement levels with low anti-dsDNA suggests minimal immune complex formation and inflammation. \u003Cstrong\u003ELow C3 level, high C4 level, high anti-dsDNA level\u003C/strong\u003E would be an unusual pattern as C3 and C4 generally move in parallel during SLE activity. \u003Cstrong\u003EHigh C3 level, low C4 level, high anti-dsDNA level\u003C/strong\u003E would also be an unusual pattern as complement levels typically decrease together during disease activity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERegular monitoring of these serological markers, along with clinical assessment and other relevant investigations (such as urinary sediment in patients with lupus nephritis), helps guide treatment decisions and predict disease flares before they may become clinically apparent. There is an increased incidence of SLE in Indigenous compared to non-Indigenous people.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Low complement levels (C3, C4) are a key marker of active systemic lupus erythematosus and can predict disease flares.","The combination of low complement and rising anti-dsDNA levels strongly suggests active disease requiring treatment modification.","There are higher rates of SLE and lupus nephritis in the Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander population."],"references":["Justiz Vaillant AA, Goyal A, Bansal P, Varacallo M. Systemic Lupus Erythematosus. In: StatPearls [online]. 2023. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK535405/","* Eades LE et al. Systemic lupus erythematosus in Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples in Australia: addressing disparities and barriers to optimising patient care. The Lancet Rheumatology. Volume 6, Issue 10, e713 - e726. Available at: 10.1016/S2665-9913(24)00095-X"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85604"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17134"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85604","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85604"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-20T11:25:55+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-